        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/{size}/34172_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-07-25T21:28:39.311Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Signal has been a touchscreen smartphone app since inception in ~2010, back when it was called TextSecure. Smartphones are 40% of all mobile phones in the world, and more powerful than feature phones, which is part of the reason they‚Äôre able to run apps like Signal.</p>\n<p>Making Signal run natively on feature phones would probably require a completely separate team from the ones that currently exist, possibly a different code base etc., which would require a lot more money. There are also no feature phones that run iOS. Since Signal is developed by a charity, this investment wouldn‚Äôt be worth it, and would take a lot of capital to just get off the ground.</p>\n<p>Admittedly, I‚Äôm a little confused why people go back to feature phones, or niche products like Light Phone, when Android and iOS already have functions that let you make operation ‚Äúdumber‚Äù, and they‚Äôve been around for years.</p>\n<p>Buying a Pixel, putting GrapheneOS on it, and then using the ‚Äúdumb down‚Äù functions already built into Android seems like a lot less effort than completely changing your lifestyle and adapting to living like it‚Äôs 2000.</p>",
